  {
    "client_msg_id": "0ca9ce3b-8b15-4393-89a1-74b1c1c73162",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "intersting, first time encountering this. Thanks for the tip! The ValOS runs the same code on node.js on servers, too, with a somewhat unorthodox approach. We have a virtual DOM running in a pretty much identical library as the front end and the back end reacts to data changes.\n\nYou can just specify a lens for the node.js server by pointing `WORKER_LENS` to a lens media. If the lens has an observable value in a function call, something like\n```\n&lt;ValaaScope focus={focus.operationToDoInTheBackEnd(focus.valueToObserve)} /&gt;\n```\nthen the back end Gateway will react to it, call the function and do stuff with it, which can for example write back to the same partition a new value, to which the front end can again react.",
    "user": "UG91ZQ26P",
    "ts": "1551110941.008800",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
